sect2.para:
Specific populations such as rural-dwelling individuals, some older adults, and those living below the poverty line may not have reliable access to the Internet or Internet-enabled devices, and therefore, telephone rather than video sessions may be the only option to facilitate care. Finally, as telehealth only recently became a feasible option for treatment, many evidence-based treatments (EBTs) previously found to be efficacious have yet to be evaluated for telehealth. Clinicians should be mindful of this when selecting appropriate EBTs for telehealth clients, though initial research shows comparable outcomes between telehealth and face-to-face interventions (Greenwood et al.,
            2022
         ).

With respect to culture, we emphasize the distinction between “different” and “pathological,” wherein the former is a subjective determination best contextualized by the culture of the client. This may be the case with cultural concepts of distress, such asataque de nervios, a constellation of physical and emotional responses to a stressor endorsed by Hispanic/Latino individuals (particularly Puerto Rican, Dominican, and Cuban individuals; Lewis-Fernández & López, 
            2016
         ). Similarly, individuals from Asian cultures may be more likely to report somatic symptoms of distress rather than emotional symptoms (Haroz et al., 
            2017
         ). Clinicians can best clarify their understanding of a client’s experience by reflecting the client’s own language and choice of vocabulary back to them during the session, with an attempt to understand the client’s meaning. Tools like the Cultural Formulation Interview (Lewis-Fernández et al., 
            2016
         ) can be utilized by clinicians to better understand the client’s cultural background and current functioning.
